In Visual Studio, pressing an open paren `(` will commit the selected item in the completion list.

eg.:

``` dart
funcA() {
}

funcB() {
  func
}
```

With the cursor after the `c` on the last line and the completion list having `funcA` selected, pressing `ENTER` will complete the item. However pressing `(` will not, it will just result in `func(`.

It would be really nice if when you register a completion item provider you can provide characters that will also commit the selection (I think it should complete and then still insert the character after the completion).

(Edit: maybe it should be a Code user-option, not a language-specific thing?)

- VSCode Version: 1.4.0
- OS Version: OS X El Capitan 10.11.6

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Create an ES6 class in JavaScript (not sure if issue is in TypeScript or not).
2. Reference that class in a method of the class.
3. Try rename using the reference symbol.
4. An info message appears "You cannot rename this element."

``` javascript
class Foo {
  do() {
    return Foo;
  }
}
```
